===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An action, state of mind, or object one has an [[obligation]] to [[perform]] for another, [[adopt]] toward another, or [[give]] to another.
#* {{quote-book|year=1589|author={{w|William Shakespeare}}|title=Henry IV, Part I|section=act 1, scene 3|passage=Revenge the jeering and disdain'd contempt / Of this proud king, who studies day and night / To answer all the '''debt''' he owes to you / Even with the bloody payment of your deaths.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1850|author={{w|Nathaniel Hawthorne}}|title={{w|The Scarlet Letter}}|chapter=14|passage=This long '''debt''' of confidence, due from me to him, whose bane and ruin I have been, shall at length be paid.}}
# The state or condition of owing something to another.
#: {{ux|en|I am in your '''debt'''.}}
# [[money|Money]] that one person or entity [[owe]]s or is required to [[pay]] to another, generally as a result of a [[loan]] or other [[financial]] transaction.
#* {{quote-book|year=1919|author={{w|Upton Sinclair}}|title=Jimmie Higgins|chapter=15|passage=Bolsheviki had repudiated the four-billion-dollar '''debt''' which the government of the Tsar had contracted with the bankers.}}
#* {{quote-magazine|date=2013-06-22|volume=407|issue=8841|page=70|magazine={{w|The Economist}}
|title=Engineers of a different kind|url=http://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21579879-buy-out-firm-really-does-focus-operational-improvements-engineers|passage=Private-equity nabobs bristle at being dubbed mere financiers. Piling '''debt''' onto companies’ balance-sheets is only a small part of what leveraged buy-outs are about, they insist. Improving the workings of the businesses they take over is just as core to their calling, if not more so. Much of their pleading is public-relations bluster.}}
# {{lb|en|legal}} An [[action]] at law to recover a certain specified sum of money alleged to be due.
#: {{rfquotek|Burrill}}

